UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426690900454
AB  - This paper demonstrates that the lower variance of spot interest rates for longer maturity Treasury bills is a function of two factors: (1) lower variance of longer maturity forward rates and (2) an averaging effect resulting from less than perfect correlation between forward interest rates. Empirically for U.S. Treasury bills, the averaging effect reinforces the lower variance of forward rates, making the spot variance relatively small for longer maturities.
